        "heading": "2.1 Electrostatic Potential",
        "body": "<p>2.1 Electrostatic Potential The electrostatic potential at any point in the region of electric field is equal to the amount of work done in bringing a unit positive test charge from infinity to that point without acceleration. If W is work done in bringing a unit positive test charge from infinity to a given point, then electric potential is given by Electrostatic potential (V) =</p><p>T YOUR PRACTICE GOAL - Objective Type Questions (37 Qs; MCQs, A-R, Matching) - Case Based Questions-3</p><p>- Subjective Questions (10 VSAs, 17 SAs, 19 LAs)</p><p>Work done (W)</p><p>Charge {q^)</p><ul><li>It is a scalar quantity and its dimensional formula is [M L^T</li></ul><p>M</p><ul><li>Its SI unit is volt (V).</li></ul><p>1 volt is simply the electrostatic potential at a point when 1 joule of work is done in bringing 1 coulomb of positive charge from infinity to that point.</p><p>- Numerical Problems-16</p><p>1V =</p><p>IJ</p><p>= lNmC</p><p>-1</p><p>1C</p><p>^TEACHER TIP Electric potential at any point is also defined as the negative line integral of electric field from infinity to given point, i.e.</p><p>V = - E-dl</p><p>AUfffOne Physics Class 12th</p>",
