        "heading": "4.1 Magnetic Field and Its",
        "body": "<p>4.1 Magnetic Field and Its Applications In this chapter, we will study about magnetism produced by a moving charge and further we will proceed with Ampere's circuital law and its applications and at last, the chapter will be</p><p>ended with magnetic force and torque between two parallel conductors.</p><p>Magnetic Field The space in the surroundings of a magnet or a current-carrying</p><p>- Objective Type Questions (34 Qs; MCQs, A-R, Matching)</p><p>conductor in which its magnetic influence can be experienced is</p><p>- Case Based Questions-2</p><p>called magnetic field.</p><p>- Subjective Questions (9 VSAs, 19 SAs, 15 LAs)</p><p>The SI unit of magnetic field is tesla (T) or weber/metre ^ -1 m (Wbm~^) or NA -i.__ and its CGS unit is gauss (G).</p><p>- Numerical Problems-16</p><p>1 tesla = 10</p><p>gauss</p><p>Dimensions ofB= (MT\"^A\"^]</p><p>Oersted's Experiment In 1820 HC Oersted discovered that an electric current creates a</p><p>magnetic field. He showed this by placing a magnetic compass near a current-carrying wire.</p><p>Moving Charges and Magnetism</p><p>When the current flowed through the wire, the needle of the compass gets deflected, proving that moving</p><p>charges produce a magnetic field around them. This experiment was a key set up in understanding the relationship between electricity and magnetism.</p><p>re</p><p>presented by the right handed screw rule or right</p><p>hand thumb rule.</p><p>Here, dB is perpendicular to the plane containing dl of the current element).</p><p>Element; Biot-Savart's Law Biot-Savart's law is an</p><ul><li>Current element</li></ul><p>experimental law predicted by Biot</p>",
