        "body": "<p>4.3 Magnetic Force and Torque Experienced by a Current Loop</p><p>X'-</p><p>7.3.1X10\"\"T</p><p>N = nAl</p><p>The total force F on the free electrons and hence on the</p><p>^ *-©-©</p><p>Vd</p><p>X</p><p>Current carrying conductor in a uniform magnetic field</p><p>Let US consider a portion of length I and cross-sectional area A of a straight conductor carrying a current /.</p><p>length / of the conductor is, therefore F = F'xN = (evj J5sin 0)(« A /) = {ne A</p><p>)BlsinQ</p><p>But current flowing through a conductor, I = neA v^ F = IB/sin0</p><p>or</p><p>F = /(lxB)</p><p>AUfftOne Physics Class 12th</p><p>Special Cases</p><p>Sol. Magnetic force on the wire, F = B//sin0 = 5//sin90°</p><p>. If0=O°orl8OMhenf = /B/sin0° = 0</p><p>= 0.27xl0x3xl0\"^x l = 8.IxlO'^N</p><p>[v sinO° = 0 and sin 180° = 0] ● If 0 = 90°, then force is maximum. F.max = 75/sin90° = /B/</p><p>[v sin 90° = 1]</p><p>Rules to Find Out the Direction of Force</p><p>The direction of the force acting on a current-carrying conductor in a magnetic field can be found by any of the following two rules,</p><p>(i) Right Hand Palm Rule If we stretch our right hand palm such that the thumb points in the direction of the current I and the stretched fingers in the direction of the magnetic field B, then the force F on the conductor will be perpendicular to the palm in the direction of pushing by the palm as shown in the Fig. (a).</p><p>[v6 = 90°]</p><p>I</p>",
