        "heading": "9.6 Prism and Optical",
        "body": "<p>9.6 Prism and Optical Instruments A prism is a portion of a</p><p>transparent medium bounded by two plane faces inclined to each other at a suitable angle. In the given figure, ABQP and ACRP are the two refracting faces and ZA is called angle of prism.</p><p>ZA+ZROQ = 180°</p><p>...(hi)</p><p>[Z A is called the angle of prism] From Eqs. (ii) and (iii), we get ri+r2=A</p><p>...(iv)</p><p>Substituting the value from Eq. (iv) in Eq. (i), we obtain 5 = (i + e) - A</p><p>If|i is the refractive index of material of the prism, then according to Snell's law.</p><p>Ray Optics and Optical Instruments sin 1</p><p>sin I 1</p><p>From Snell's law,</p><p>l^=-</p><p>l^ = sin r</p><p>sinr 1</p><p>When angles are small, sinij = [i=—</p><p>and sinrj =</p><p>A+ 5 m sm</p><p>[here, f, = i]</p><p>I = jari</p><p>l^ =</p><p>ij</p><p>Similarly,</p><p>1^ = —</p><p>e or</p><p>A sm</p><p>V ^2</p><p>=-</p><p>^2</p><p>This relation is called a prism formula.</p><p>e=pr2</p><p>For thin prisms (i.e. A is very small), the value of</p><p>6 =i+e-A</p><p>= |xri + p.r2 - A = H(ri + r2)-A</p><p>A + 5m sm</p><p>h+'-2 = A 5 = |M-A</p><p>But</p><p>So, sm</p><p>A+6 m</p><p>A</p><p>—</p><p>A/2</p><p>5 = (p-l)A</p><p>or</p><p>This is the angle through which a ray deviates on passing through a thin prism of small refracting</p>",
