        "body": "<p>12.3 Electron Orbits</p><p>12.1 a-Particles Scattering Experiment by Rutherford This experiment was suggested by Rutherford in 1911 as given in the figure below</p><p>12,4 Bohr's Model of Hydrogen Atom 12,5 Hydrogen Spectrum or Line</p><p>Radioactive Most of the</p><p>source of a-particles</p><p>Spectra of Hydrogen Atom</p><p>Gold foil</p><p>(10'® m thick)</p><p>ft ▼</p><p>a</p><p>a T</p><p>ZnS</p><p>Lead cavity</p><p>- Objective Type Questions (28 Qs; MCQs, A-R, Matching)</p><p>screen</p><p>Collimator</p><p>About one a-particle in 8000</p><p>- Case Based Questions-2</p><p>a-particles is reflected back</p><p>- Subjective Questions (6 VSAs, 7 SAs, 6 LAs) - Numerical Prob!ems-10</p><p>a-particles pass in straight line</p><p>\"'</p><p>Microscope detector</p><p>Experimental arrangement for Rutherford's theory 214</p><p>In this experiment, H.Geiger and E.Marsden took 83 Bi as a source for a-particles. A collimated beam of a-particles of</p><p>energy 5.5 MeV was allowed to fall on 2.1 x 10~^ m thick gold foil.</p><p>The a-particles were observed by a rotatable detector consisting of a zinc sulphide screen and microscope, it was found that a-particles got scattered and produced bright flashes or scintillations on the zinc sulphide screen, these scintillations were counted at different</p><p>angles from the direction of incident beam.</p><p>Conclusions</p><p>On the basis of his experiment, Rutherford concluded that</p><p>(i) Atom has a lot of empty space and practically the entire mass of the atom is confined at extremely small central core called nucleus, whose size is of the</p><p>Note Gold is preferred in this experiment due to its malleable</p><p>order from 10</p><p>-15</p><p>m to 10</p><p>-14</p><p>m.</p><p>properties.</p><p>(ii) Scattering ofa-particles (positively charged) is due to</p><p>Observations</p><p>the Coulomb's law of electrostatic force of repulsion</p><p>Rutherford made the following observations from his experiment:</p><p>(i) Most of the a-particles passed through the gold foil, it means they do not suffer any collision, (ii) Only about 0.14% of the incident a-particles scattered by more than 1°. (iii) About one a-particle in every 8000 a-particles deflected by more than 90°. The total number of a-particles {N) scattered</p><p>through an angle (0) is as shown in the figure below</p><p>q5</p><p>o</p><p>IS</p><p>QJ</p><p>a-Particle Trajectory The a-particle experiences deflection due to repulsive electrostatic force of nucleus when passes through the atom.</p><p>the nucleus</p><p>10®</p><p>\"D -o</p><p>(iv) The a-particles that pass at a large distance from the nucleus go almost undeviated.</p><ul><li>deflection is very large when a-particle passes close to</li></ul><p>10^ ■c</p><p>g.</p><p>between the positive charge of nucleus and a-particles. (iii) Distance between electron and nucleus is from 10^ to 10^ times the size of the nucleus itself</p><ul><li>deflection is very small when a-particle passes far away</li></ul><p>in5</p><p>from the nucleus.</p><p>10^</p><p>T3</p><p>10^ n</p><p>E</p><p>1Q2 10</p><p>100 120 140 160</p><p>Scattering angle 9 (in degree)</p><p>Experimental data points (shown by dots) on scattering of a-particles by a thin foil at different angles</p><p>(iv) The number of a-particles scattered per unit area N(0) at scattering angle 0 varies inversely as sin'^0/2. N(0)</p><p>sin'^ 0/2</p><p>(v) The force between a-particles and nucleus is given by F =</p><p>4m 0</p><p>{2e){Ze) r</p><p>where, r is the distance between the a-particles and the nucleus. This force is directed along the line joining the a-particle and the nucleus. The</p><p>magnitude and direction of this force on a-particle continuously changes as it approaches the nucleus and recedes away from it.</p><p>4 5</p><p>Trajectory of a-particles close to an atom</p><p>The a-particles which travel towards the nucleus directly, slow down, comes to rest and ultimately repelled back and retrace their path at 180°.</p><p>1 OC</p><p>Distance of Closest Approach At a certain distance Tq from the nucleus, KE of a-particle reduces to zero. The particle stops and cannot go further close to the nucleus due to the strong repulsive force of nucleus. This distance Yq is known as the distance of closest approach and it can be define as The distance of charged particle from the centre of the nucleus (rp) at which complete kinetic energy of</p><p>Atoms</p><p>the charged particle gets converted into the electric potential energy of the system, a-particle</p><p>''</p><p>'\\Nucleus</p><p>K-A+Ze)</p><p>(+2e)</p><p>r</p><p>The force between a-particles and nucleus is given by 1</p><p>(2e)(Ze)</p><p>4m 0</p><p>r</p><p>F =</p><p>KE of a-particle = Electrostatic potential energy iZe){2e)</p><p>['.● charge on a-particle is -l- 2e and charge on nucleus is Ze, where Z is atomic number] ^0 =</p><p>2Ze^</p><p>4m 0</p><p>K</p><p>^0 =</p><p>fl</p><p>4m 0</p><p>Ze(2e) _ 2Ze^</p><p>2x 79x (1.6X 10\"^^)^ X 9x 10^ 4X 10</p><p>-14</p><p>= 9.1X 10\"^^ J</p><p>Angle of Scattering (0) Angle by which a-particle gets deviated from its original path around the nucleus is called angle of</p><p>Impact Parameter (b) Perpendicular distance of the velocity vector of a-particle from the central line of the nucleus of the atom is called impact parameter. Mathematically, it is expressed as</p><p>2Ze^</p><p>1 or</p><p>Sol. Here, closest distance of approach, Tq = 4x Atomic number, Z = 79, KE,- = ?</p><p>scattering.</p><p>4m 0</p><p>energy of cx-particle.</p><p>At the distance of closest approach, 1</p><p>approach is 4 x 10\"^\"^ m. Calculate the initial kinetic</p><p>KE^ of a-particle =</p><p>where, r is the distance between the a-particles and the nucleus. The magnitude and direction of this force on a-particle continuously changes as it approaches the nucleus and recedes away from it.</p><p>K =</p>",
