        "heading": "12.2 Rutherford's Model",
        "body": "<p>12.2 Rutherford's Model of Atom</p><p>Quick Test 1 1. Explain briefly how Rutherford scattering of a-particle by a target nucleus can provide information of the size of the nucleus?</p><p>The essential features of Rutherford's nuclear model of the atom are as follows</p><p>(i) Every atom consists of a central core, called the atomic nucleus, in which the entire positive charge and almost entire mass of the atom is concentrated,</p><p>(ii) The size of nucleus is of the order of 10\"'^m, which is very small as compared to the size of the atom which is of the order of 10 \"^^m.</p><p>(iii)The atomic nucleus is surrounded by certain number of electrons which is equal to the total positive charge in the nucleus. Thus, atom becomes electrically neutral,</p><p>2. An a -particle of kinetic energy K is bombarded on a thin gold foil. The distance of the closest approach is r. What will be the distance of closest approach for an a -particle of double the kinetic energy? 3. What is the impact parameter for scattering of a-particle by 180°? 4. What is the ratio of mass of an a -particle to that of an electron? 5. Why is the classical (Rutherford) model for an atom of electron orbiting around the nucleus not able to explain the atomic structure?</p><p>6. The number ofa-particles scattered at 90° is 50 per minute. What will be the number ofa-particles, when it is scattered at an angle of I20°?</p><p>Answers</p><p>(iv) These electrons revolve around the nucleus in</p><p>various circular orbits as same as the planets revolve</p><p>3. 0</p><p>around the sun.</p><p>For Solutions, See QR Code on Pg. 401</p><p>The centripetal force required by electrons for revolution is provided by the electrostatic force of</p><p>4.7341</p>",
