        "heading": "12.4 Bohr's Model of Hydrogen Atom",
        "body": "<p>12.4 Bohr's Model of Hydrogen Atom Bohr combined classical and early quantum concepts and gave his theory in the form of three postulates. These three postulates are as follows (i) Bohr's first postulate was that an electron in an atom revolves in certain stable orbits without the</p><p>emission of radiant energy, i.e. each atom has</p><p>jn^ or r„o^n^i</p><p>where, e q = permittivity of vacuum h = Planck's constant</p><p>= mass of electron and</p><p>n is also known as principal quantum number.</p><p>For n = 1 and putting values of constants, we get</p><p>X (6.63X10'^^)^ m -31 3.14x9.1x10 X (1.6x10\"^^)^ 8.85x10</p><p>^0</p><p>= 5.29X10</p><p>-11</p><p>certain definite stable states in which it can exist and</p><p>each possible state has definite total energy. These are called the stationary states of the atom.</p><p>-12</p><p>Tq = 0.53 A This is called Bohr radius.</p><p>m</p><p>0.53 A</p><p>Since, r„ = 0.53 x n^A, the radius of the second orbit of</p><p>Total energy, £(eV)</p><p>H-atom will be (4 xO.53) A and that of the third orbit (9x0.53) A.</p><p>Unbound (ionised)</p><p>/</p><p>Note Velocity and energy of electron in stationary orbits of</p><p>hydrogen atoms are given by V,</p><p>2htr.n 0</p><p>and E,</p><p>atom</p><p>n=5</p><p>-0.85</p><p>me*</p><p>&amp;eln^h^</p><p>n=4</p><p>-1,51</p><p>n~3</p><p>-3.40</p><p>n=2</p><p>Excited states</p>",
