        "heading": "13.4 Nuclear Energy",
        "body": "<p>13.4 Nuclear Energy Nuclear energy is the energy released during the transformation of nuclei with less total binding energy to the nuclei with greater binding energy. Two distinct ways of obtaining energy from nucleus are as follows: 1. Nuclear fission</p><p>2. Nuclear fusion</p><p>Answers</p><p>8. (i) 23x10*'kg/m^ (iii) Z3X10*' kg/m^ 9. l-axlO*\")</p><p>JO. 104.67 MeV</p><p>For Solutions, See QR Code on Pg. 423 235</p><p>In fission, a heavy nucleus like 92 U breaks into two smaller fragments by the bombardment of thermal neutron (low energy or slow moving), e.g.</p><p>141 56</p><p>Ba + 3gKr -I- 3 q «* + Q (Energy released)</p><p>Q-value here refer to the energy released in the nuclear process, which can be determined using</p><p>Nuclear Fission</p><p>Einstein's mass-energy relation, E = mc^.</p><p>Nuclear fission is the phenomenon of splitting of a</p><ul><li>The Q-value is equal to the difference of mass of products and reactants multiplied by square of velocity 235 of light. Energy released per fission of 92 Uis</li></ul><p>heavy nucleus (usually A &gt; 230) into two or more lighter nuclei by the bombardment of proton, neutron, cc-particle, etc. Energies associated with nuclear processes are about a million times larger than chemical process.</p><p>NCERT</p><p>200.4 MeV.</p><p>Alb'nOne Physics Class 12th</p><ul><li>The fragment nuclei produced in fission are highly unstable. They are highly radioactive and emit 3-particles in succession until each reaches to a stable end product. Nuclear Chain Reaction In the nuclear fission reaction, there is a release of extra</li></ul><p>neutrons. The extra neutrons bring about the fission of three more nuclei and produce nine neutrons, which in turn can bring about the fission of nine nuclei and so</p><p>Nuclear Fusion Nuclear fusion is the phenomenon of fusing of two or more lighter nuclei forming a single heavy nucleus. For fusion to take place, the two nuclei must come close enough so that nuclear force is able to affect them. Since both the nuclei experience coulomb's repulsion. Therefore, they must have enough energy to overcome this coulomb barrier. e.g.</p><p>-&gt; ,H ^ + 1 + V -h 0.42 MeV ^2He^-t-o«* + 3.27 MeV ^iH^-l-iH'-h4.03 MeV</p><p>I</p><p>on. Thus, a continuous chain of nuclear fission is</p><p>set-up called nuclear chain reaction. It starts a huge amount of energy release in short time (in few microseconds).</p><p>The chain reactions may be of two types (i) Uncontrolled Chain Reaction During fission reaction, released neutrons causes further fissions,</p><p>then number of fissions increase rapidly with time. So, the reaction becomes very fast and huge amount</p><p>of energy is liberated in each fission with violent explosion. The cycle repeats to give a self-sustaining chain reaction and gives off energy at a rate that increases rapidly with time. This is called uncontrolled chain reaction. It is used in nuclear bomb,</p><p>(ii) Controlled Chain Reaction By some means, the reaction is controlled in such a way that only one of</p><ul><li>Fusion of hydrogen nuclei into helium nuclei is the source of energy of most of the stars including the sun.</li></ul><p>^TEACHER TIP ● Unstable nucleus undergoes a decay, this is referred to as radioactive decay. Three types of radioactive decay occur in nature</p><ul><li>a-decay in which a helium nucleus He is emitted.</li><li>p-decay in which electrons or positrons are emitted.</li><li>Y-decay in which high energy photons are emitted.</li></ul><p>Energy Generation in Stars Thermonuclear fusion is the source of energy in the stars. The interior of the sun has a temperature of</p><p>l.SxlO^K, which is considerably less than the estimated</p><p>fission, then the fission rate remains constant and</p><p>temperature required for fusion of particles of average energy. Fusion in the sun involves protons whose energies are much above the average energy.</p><p>the energy is released steadily. Such a chain</p><p>When fusion is achieved by raising the temperature</p><p>the neutrons emitted in a fission causes another</p><p>reaction is called a controlled chain reaction. ● It is used in a nuclear reactor.</p><p>The sustained feasibility of nuclear chain reaction depends on the multiplication factor or reproduction factor K. K =</p><p>Rate of production of neutrons Rate of loss of neutrons</p><ul><li>If iC = 1, the operation of reactor is said to be critical. It is what we wish to be for steady power operation.</li><li>If K &gt; 1, the reaction rate and reactor power increases</li></ul><p>exponentially. In this case, reaction is super-critical and can even explode. ● If iC &lt; 1, the reaction gradually stops, and the condition is called sub-critical.</p><p>of the system, so that particles have enough KE to overcome the coulomb repulsive behaviour. It is called thermonuclear fusion.</p><p>The fusion reaction in the sun is a multi-step process in</p><p>which the hydrogen is fused into helium. The proton-proton (p, p) cycle by which this occurs is represented by the following sets of reactions:</p><p>|h + | H ^ fH-be'\"+v-t-0.42MeV e*-¥e~ ^ Y-I-Y +1.02 MeV</p><p>^2He-hY +5.49 MeV iHe+lUe ^ ^ He-K{H-l-lH-M2.86MeV</p><p>...(ii) ...(iii) ...(iv)</p><p>For the fourth reaction to occur, the first three</p><p>reactions must occur twice, in case two light helium nuclei unite to form ordinary helium nucleus. If we consider the combination 2(i)-l- 2(ii)+ 2(iii)-l-(iv), the net effect is</p><p>4lH + 2e\"</p><p>^He-b2v-l-6Y + 26.7 MeV</p><p>Nuclei</p><p>or</p><p>B = ^ = 100 = 100J</p><p>(4}H + 4e )^(2He+2e\")+2v+6Y + 26.7MeV</p><p>t</p><p>Thus, four hydrogen atoms combine to form 2 He atom with a release of 26.7 MeV of energy. ● As the hydrogen in the core gets depleted and becomes helium, the core starts to cool. The star</p><p>begins to collapse under its own gravity, which</p><p>Time for which bulb will glow 15.696 x 10 100</p><p>estimated that there is enough hydrogen in the sun to keep it going for another 5 billion years. Controlled Thermonuclear Fusion</p><p>The natural thermonuclear fusion in a star is replicated in a thermonuclear fusion device. The aim of controlled</p><p>thermonuclear fusion is to generate the steady power by heating the nuclear fuel to a temperature in the</p><p>range of 10 ^K. At these temperature, the fuel is a</p><p>mixture of positive ions and electrons (plasma). The challenge is to confine this plasma, since no container can stand such a high temperature. Several countries around the world including India are developing techniques in this connection. If successful, fusion reactors will hopefully, supply almost unlimited power to humanity.</p>",
