        "heading": "14.5 Semiconductor Diode",
        "body": "<p>14.5 Semiconductor Diode</p><p>or p-n Junction Diode It is basically a p-n junction with metallic contacts provided at the ends for the application of an external voltage. It is a two terminal device.</p><ul><li>It is represented by the symbol</li></ul><p>Just at this moment, an electron is released from the</p><p>negative terminal of the battery which enters the</p><p>w-region to replace the electron lost by combining with a hole at the junction. Thus, a current called forward current is constituted by the motion of majority charge carriers across the junction. In forward bias, the junction diode offers low resistance.</p><ul><li>The direction of arrow indicates the conventional direction of current.</li></ul><p>Forward Biasing and Reverse Biasing of Junction Diode Biasing is the method of connecting external battery or emf source to a p-n junction diode. The junction diode can be connected to an external battery in two ways, called forward biasing and reverse biasing of the</p><p>Reverse Biasing A junction diode is said to be reverse biased when the</p><p>positive terminal of the external battery is connected to the n-side and negative terminal to the p-side of the diode.</p><p>Flow of Current in Reverse Biasing In this situation, the</p><p>junction.</p><p>reverse voltage supports the potential barrier, due</p><p>Forward Biasing</p><p>to which both the</p><p>A junction diode is said to be forward biased when the</p><p>potential barrier and width of the depletion layer increases.</p><p>positive terminal of the external battery is connected to the p-side and negative terminal to the n-side of the diode.</p><p>Flow of Current in Forward Biasing In this situation, the forward voltage opposes the potential barrier, due to which both the potential barrier and width of the depletion layer decreases.</p><p>Under the effect of</p><p>external electric field,</p><p>Junction</p><p>Hole</p><p>p-region</p><p>n region</p><p>^Flpctrnn</p><p>E*^</p><p>Battery</p><p>Reverse biasing of junction diode</p><p>Under the effect of external electric field, holes in the</p><p>holes in the p-region and electrons in the n-region are pushed away from the junction i.e. they cannot be combined at the junction. So, there is almost no flow of current due to majority</p><p>p-region and electrons in the n-region, both move</p><p>charge carriers.</p><p>towards the junction.</p><p>Semiconductor Electronics : Materials, Devices and Simple Circuits</p><p>However, a very small current due to minority charge carriers flows across the junction. This current is called reverse current.</p><ul><li>Therefore, the small reverse current remains almost</li></ul><p>constant over a sufficiently long range of reverse bias,</p><p>increasing very little with increasing voltage (OC</p><p>I-V Characteristics of p-n Junction Diode</p><p>portion of the graph). n</p><p>Reverse voltage (V)</p><p>The graphical relations between voltage applied across p-n junction and current flowing through the junction</p><p>-10</p><p>-8</p><p>-6</p><p>-4</p><p>-2</p><p>T</p><p>are called I-V characteristics of junction diode.</p><p>0 0</p><p>C</p><p>.1</p><p>Forward Biased Characteristics</p><p>3 o</p><p>Breakdown</p><p>The circuit diagram for studying forward biased characteristics is shown in the figure (a). Starting from a low value, forward bias voltage is increased step by step (measured by voltmeter) and forward current is noted (by ammeter). A graph is plotted between voltage and current is shown in figure (b).</p><p>1 2 e &lt;D</p><p>voltage</p><p>«</p><p>(U &gt; QJ</p><p>Battery</p><p>cc</p><p>D</p><p>(b). (a) Reverse biased characteristic of a diode</p><ul><li>This reverse current is voltage independent upto</li></ul><p>certain voltage known as breakdown voltage and this voltage independent current is called reverse</p><p>n</p><p>B</p><p>^6</p><p>saturation current.</p><p>cE5</p><p>mA,</p><p>Avalanche Breakdown</p><p>Ge</p><p>I3 WWW-</p><p>i2 2 1</p><p>I-</p><p>Battery (a)</p><p>knee voltage</p><p>0.1</p><p>(b)</p><p>0.2</p><p>0.3</p><p>0,4</p><p>0-5</p><p>Forward voltage (V)_</p><p>Forward biased characteristic of a diode</p><p>If the reverse bias is equal to the breakdown voltage, then the reverse current through the junction increases very rapidly (CD portion of the graph), this situation is called avalanche breakdown and the junction may get</p><p>damaged due to excessive heating if this current exceeds the rated value of p-n junction.</p><p>Dynamic Resistance ● The current through the diode is almost zero at low voltage, due to the potential barrier, which oppose the applied voltage.</p><ul><li>When applied voltage exceeds the potential barrier, the current starts increasing slowly. Further, increase in applied voltage, the current increases very rapidly {AB portion of the graph).</li><li>The forward voltage beyond which the current</li></ul><p>through the junction starts increasing rapidly with voltage is called knee voltage or threshold voltage</p><p>In diodes, a resistance is offered by the function which</p><p>depends on the applied voltage, which is called dynamic resistance. It is the ratio of small change in voltage to the small change in current produced. AV</p><p>Dynamic resistance,</p>",
